Steps to Implement:

Create the CardComponent:

Use @Input to pass data to the component (e.g., the list of buttons).

Use ng-content or ng-template to provide slots for dynamic content like buttons.

Example Implementation:

CardComponent (Child):

import { Component, Input } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-card',
  templateUrl: './card.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./card.component.css']
})
export class CardComponent {
  @Input() title: string = '';  // Title for the card
  @Input() description: string = '';  // Description for the card
  @Input() buttons: any[] = [];  // Array of buttons (can be of type {label: string, action: Function})
}


CardComponent HTML Template (Child):

<div class="card">
  <div class="card-header">
    <h3>{{ title }}</h3>
  </div>
  <div class="card-body">
    <p>{{ description }}</p>
    <div class="card-buttons">
      <!-- Iterate through the buttons passed by the parent -->
      <button *ngFor="let button of buttons" (click)="button.action()">
        {{ button.label }}
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>


Here, the buttons array contains objects, each with a label (the text to show on the button) and an action (the function to execute when clicked).

CardComponent Styles (Child):

.card {
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 16px;
  width: 300px;
}

.card-header {
  font-size: 1.5rem;
  font-weight: bold;
}

.card-body {
  padding: 10px 0;
}

.card-buttons {
  margin-top: 10px;
}

.card-buttons button {
  margin-right: 5px;
  padding: 8px 16px;
  cursor: pointer;
}


Parent Component (Parent):

Now, in the Parent Component, you can pass dynamic buttons as an array to the CardComponent.

import { Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-parent',
  templateUrl: './parent.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./parent.component.css']
})
export class ParentComponent {
  cardTitle = 'Sample Card';
  cardDescription = 'This is a sample card description.';

  // Define buttons dynamically here
  cardButtons = [
    { label: 'Edit', action: this.edit },
    { label: 'Delete', action: this.delete }
  ];

  edit() {
    console.log('Edit clicked');
  }

  delete() {
    console.log('Delete clicked');
  }
}


Parent Component HTML (Parent):

<app-card [title]="cardTitle" [description]="cardDescription" [buttons]="cardButtons"></app-card>


Here, weâ€™re passing the title, description, and buttons array to the CardComponent. The buttons array contains objects with label and action properties that correspond to the dynamic buttons.

Explanation:

Dynamic Buttons: The CardComponent accepts an array of button objects. Each object has a label for the button text and an action which is a function (method) that will be called when the button is clicked.

ngFor: The buttons are rendered dynamically by iterating through the buttons array using *ngFor.

Input Binding: The CardComponent accepts the data (like title, description, and buttons) from the parent component via @Input properties.

Benefits:

Reusability: This component is highly reusable. You can pass any dynamic data (buttons or other content) to it.

Separation of Concerns: The CardComponent is focused only on rendering the card structure and doesn't need to know about the specific functionality of the buttons.

Flexibility: The parent component has full control over the buttons, and new buttons can be added easily without modifying the CardComponent.

Alternative Approach (Using ng-content):

If you want even more flexibility and allow the parent to control the exact layout of the card, including the buttons, you can use ng-content.

<div class="card">
  <div class="card-header">
    <h3>{{ title }}</h3>
  </div>
  <div class="card-body">
    <p>{{ description }}</p>
    <ng-content></ng-content>  <!-- Slot for dynamic content like buttons -->
  </div>
</div>


Now in the parent component:

<app-card [title]="cardTitle" [description]="cardDescription">
  <button (click)="edit()">Edit</button>
  <button (click)="delete()">Delete</button>
</app-card>
